content:
Designing an HTML page with a form that includes multiple text fields and dropdown lists is a straightforward process. Below is a simple example to get you started. This example includes a basic HTML structure with a form that contains text fields for user input and dropdown lists for selection.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Sample Form</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        form {
            max-width: 400px;
            margin: auto;
        }
        div {
            margin-bottom: 15px;
        }
        label {
            display: block;
            margin-bottom: 5px;
        }
        input[type="text"], select {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 8px;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h2>Sample Form</h2>
    <form action="#" method="post">
        <!-- Text Field for Name -->
        <div>
            <label for="name">Name:</label>
            <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required>
        </div>

        <!-- Text Field for Email -->
        <div>
            <label for="email">Email:</label>
            <input type="text" id="email" name="email" required>
        </div>

        <!-- Dropdown for Gender -->
        <div>
            <label for="gender">Gender:</label>
            <select id="gender" name="gender" required>
                <option value="">Select...</option>
                <option value="male">Male</option>
                <option value="female">Female</option>
                <option value="other">Other</option>
            </select>
        </div>

        <!-- Dropdown for Country -->
        <div>
            <label for="country">Country:</label>
            <select id="country" name="country" required>
                <option value="">Select...</option>
                <option value="india">India</option>
                <option value="usa">United States</option>
                <option value="uk">United Kingdom</option>
                <option value="canada">Canada</option>
                <!-- Add more countries as needed -->
            </select>
        </div>

        <!-- Submit Button -->
        <div>
            <button type="submit">Submit</button>
        </div>
    </form>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:

- **HTML Structure**: The document starts with a standard HTML structure, including `<!DOCTYPE html>` and `<html>` tags. It includes a `<head>` section for metadata and styles, and a `<body>` section for content.

- **Form Elements**: Inside the `<form>` tag, various form elements like text fields and dropdown lists are included.

  - **Text Fields**: These are created using `<input type="text">` for capturing text data like name and email.

  - **Dropdown Lists**: These are created using `<select>` and `<option>` tags. Each `<option>` represents a selectable item within the dropdown.

- **Styling**: Basic CSS is used to enhance the appearance of the form. This includes styling for the form layout, labels, inputs, and the submit button.

Feel free to customize the form by adding more fields, adjusting styles, or modifying the options in the dropdown lists to suit your needs.
